1 Adding Variables to Our Data

To begin, I made some small adjustments to the original data set. Now we have both an area and density variable, both of which will be used in the next two plots.

swz_adm1 <- swz_adm1 %>% 
  mutate(area = st_area(swz_adm1) %>% set_units("km^2"),
         density = pop20 / area)

2 Making a Bar Plot

Next, I made a bar plot to compare the populations for each region of Eswatini.

This bar plot goes nicely with a spatial representation of population distribution across the four regions of Esawtini. To add in additional information, I set the bar plot on the same axes as an earlier plot. This time, however, the numbers under the names of each region signify the population density of that region in people per km2.

3 A Challenge

I liked the information that was conveyed in Individual Stretch Goal 1, but I found it a little hard to read. I instead opted to go for a plot that displayed similar information, while also being easier to read. To achieve this, I used the ggplot2::facet_wrap() function and a geom_point() layer.

4 Zooming in on the Manzini Region

Recreating these plots for just Manzini is pretty easy. Since we already have the necessary elements (included in the raster::extract() process from a previous exercise), we just need to filter the tinkhundla that are part of Manzini (Ekukhanyeni, Kwaluseni, Lamgabhi, Lobamba Lomdzala, Ludzeludze, Mafutseni, Mahlangatja, Mangcongco, Manzini North, Manzini South, Mhlambanyatsi, Mkhiweni, Mthongwaneni, Ngwenpisi, Nhlambeni, and Ntondozi).

just_manzini <- swz_adm2 %>% filter(NAME_1 == "Manzini")

just_manzini <- just_manzini %>% mutate(area = st_area(just_manzini) %>% set_units("km^2"), 
                                        density = pop20 / area)

Then, we just need to recreate the plots. I didnt include the challenge plot in this step because, since the data didnt change (I used the GADM shapefiles throughout, which only includes first and second level administrative boundaries), the challenge plot didnt convey much new information.

Since the spatial plot is a little cramped already, Im instead including a table that relates the information about the density in each tinkhundla in Manzini.
